governance" regimes in developing countries; and the current human catastrophe we are experiencing from our seemingly inevitable move toward global ecological destruction? These are some of the many questions answered by the authors in this book. Critical thinking on cultural imperialism now cuts across many academic disciplines and subfields of interdisciplinary study. This is clearly reflected in the contents of the current book, which offers a diverse range of essays on the state of current research, knowledge, and global political action and debate on cultural imperialism. These 19 chapters, written by authors coming from many fields of interest and geographical backgrounds, provide compelling evidence of the close connection between cultural imperialism and the global power structure and the political and economic objectives behind current American attempts at global domination. However, as several of the chapters also show, cultural imperialism is certainly, historically, not an American invention, and it will probably long outlive the current American Empire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCulture diffusion. 0aGlobalizationxSocial aspects. 0aImperialism. 4aCoursebook. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aAlojamiento, Sheilfa B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Elvira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDieter, Hermann H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGermann, Christophe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoonatilake, Susantha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamm, Bernd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamm, Bernd, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators